<subSubSection pageId="80" pageNumber="81" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="80.[151,1437,151,1503]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1370,1395]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Comments.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[633,788,1370,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Baccha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="telescopica">
<emphasis box="[633,647,1372,1395]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[662,788,1370,1395]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">telescopica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the sub-scutellar fringe has much longer pile, the 
<number box="[1412,1426,1371,1395]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" value="1.0">1</number>
st abdominal segment is entirely white pilose, and the surstylus and postgonite are distinctive.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="80" pageNumber="81" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="80.[151,1437,151,1503]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1442,1467]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to the unique characteristics of the 
<typeStatus box="[1032,1080,1443,1467]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">type</typeStatus>
specimen when compared to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Baccha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="telescopica">
<emphasis box="[1415,1429,1444,1467]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,277,1478,1503]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">telescopica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is to be treated as an adjective.
</paragraph>
